00:51:09.630 --> 00:51:16.210
&gt;&gt; One thing that really
struck me was you talking

00:51:16.210 --> 00:51:19.870
about your book being a love
letter to Hampton, Virginia.

00:51:19.870 --> 00:51:23.160
I went to Tuskegee
University at HBCUs.

00:51:23.160 --> 00:51:26.970
Our islands of excellence,
where we do see people who look

00:51:26.970 --> 00:51:30.540
like us, where you do see
examples of black success,

00:51:30.540 --> 00:51:32.420
and that makes such
a huge difference

00:51:32.420 --> 00:51:34.560
when you go forth in the world.

00:51:34.560 --> 00:51:38.480
I guess my question
is, HBCUs seem to be

00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:40.780
on the decline in some ways now.

00:51:40.780 --> 00:51:43.580
The towns that surround
them aren't doing as well.

00:51:43.580 --> 00:51:46.440
Not as many students want to go.

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:49.280
And I'm wondering, what does
that mean for the future?

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:51.960
Where do the Katherine
Johnsons come from?

00:51:51.960 --> 00:51:55.190
And where's the community
that's going to nurture them

00:51:55.190 --> 00:51:58.010
and tell them that they can
do anything, especially given,

00:51:58.010 --> 00:52:01.670
using your word, the
Zeitgeist of the time?

00:52:01.670 --> 00:52:03.590
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly: I think
that's a great question.

00:52:03.590 --> 00:52:06.580
I mean, my mom went
to Hampton University,

00:52:06.580 --> 00:52:08.420
my dad went to Norfolk State.

00:52:08.420 --> 00:52:11.810
All of these women were the
products of black colleges.

00:52:11.810 --> 00:52:16.080
I was just driving around
Baltimore today doing research

00:52:16.080 --> 00:52:20.890
for the book, and Morgan State
is there, and I think, you know,

00:52:20.890 --> 00:52:23.850
there are new buildings
and, you know,

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:25.850
obviously there's
a lot of energy.

00:52:25.850 --> 00:52:29.120
Coppin State, which is also
there, has less energy.

00:52:29.120 --> 00:52:31.160
You know, I mean, it's sort of--

00:52:31.160 --> 00:52:35.720
there are issues that are
facing many, many institutions

00:52:35.720 --> 00:52:38.110
of higher education,
not just black colleges,

00:52:38.110 --> 00:52:41.820
but a lot of the black colleges
are really feeling these issues.

00:52:41.820 --> 00:52:44.620
And that was, I mean, I went
to the University of Virginia,

00:52:44.620 --> 00:52:47.990
you know, so my parents went
to black colleges, I didn't,

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:53.030
and so doing this
research, it was a real,

00:52:53.030 --> 00:53:00.480
just an amazing full
panoramic view of the support

00:53:00.480 --> 00:53:03.440
and the excellence, the
concentration of talent,

00:53:03.440 --> 00:53:06.870
particularly during
that time period.

00:53:06.870 --> 00:53:09.250
And, you know, but I
think, for example,

00:53:09.250 --> 00:53:13.570
Spellman is a tremendous success
story, you know, when you talk

00:53:13.570 --> 00:53:17.200
about the intersection of
black colleges and STEM,

00:53:17.200 --> 00:53:18.500
they're doing extremely well.

00:53:18.500 --> 00:53:20.940
I think Spellman
College graduates,

00:53:20.940 --> 00:53:27.140
or sends more black women
to STEM Ph.D. programs

00:53:27.140 --> 00:53:29.200
than any other school
in the country.

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:30.500
I think that may be true.

00:53:30.500 --> 00:53:33.870
You know, and I think this
is also an issue, you know,

00:53:33.870 --> 00:53:39.030
women's colleges, which
was another huge feeder

00:53:39.030 --> 00:53:42.880
for these jobs at NASA
and many other jobs.

00:53:42.880 --> 00:53:46.800
So I think that is a really,
really great question.

00:53:46.800 --> 00:53:53.410
And, you know, the HBCUs I
feel were another character

00:53:53.410 --> 00:53:55.170
