feel like when I wrote the book?

00:54:22.840 --> 00:54:28.180
&gt;&gt; What did you feel like when
you wrote the book or the film?

00:54:28.180 --> 00:54:32.090
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly:
What did I feel like?

00:54:32.090 --> 00:54:35.390
Wow. No, this is a
really good question.

00:54:35.390 --> 00:54:40.320
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Because
we all felt something

00:54:40.320 --> 00:54:42.200
when we read the book.

00:54:42.200 --> 00:54:44.690
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly: Well,
you know, I have to say,

00:54:44.690 --> 00:54:50.320
the thing is it was really hard.

00:54:52.130 --> 00:54:57.380
It was really, it was both
really, really enjoyable,

00:54:57.380 --> 00:55:02.740
and just I loved the research,
and I loved the writing,

00:55:02.740 --> 00:55:06.930
but it was really hard,
it was hard, it was hard.

00:55:06.930 --> 00:55:08.800
And a lot of it was hard
because I wish I could get

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:13.290
up in the morning and write at
8:00 with a cup of coffee and,

00:55:13.290 --> 00:55:16.170
you know, like Graham Greene
I guess supposedly did that,

00:55:16.170 --> 00:55:17.740
and just sat down and write.

00:55:17.740 --> 00:55:19.040
But you know what?

00:55:19.040 --> 00:55:20.910
I waste the entire day.

00:55:20.910 --> 00:55:23.730
And then I don't
really start writing

00:55:23.730 --> 00:55:27.280
until it's like 11:30 at night.

00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:29.170
And that's really painful.

00:55:29.170 --> 00:55:30.470
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: That's common.

00:55:30.470 --> 00:55:31.770
That's common.

00:55:31.770 --> 00:55:33.070
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly: I wish it
were different, but it's not.

00:55:33.070 --> 00:55:34.370
&gt;&gt; Donna Gigliotti:
11:30 in the morning?

00:55:34.370 --> 00:55:35.670
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly:
No, at night.

00:55:35.670 --> 00:55:36.970
&gt;&gt; Donna Gigliotti: Oh.

00:55:36.970 --> 00:55:38.380
[ Laughter ]

00:55:38.380 --> 00:55:39.810
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly: The
most productive time is

00:55:39.810 --> 00:55:42.930
from like 11:30 at night
until 4:00 in the morning.

00:55:42.930 --> 00:55:44.230
That is a good time to work.

00:55:44.230 --> 00:55:45.530
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: I
agree with you.

00:55:45.530 --> 00:55:46.830
I agree with you.

00:55:46.830 --> 00:55:48.130
No, but people don't
realize, I think,

00:55:48.130 --> 00:55:51.250
that a lot of the writing,
when you're writing a book,

00:55:51.250 --> 00:55:52.960
it's up here, you're
thinking it,

00:55:52.960 --> 00:55:55.250
and you can be doing
the laundry,

00:55:55.250 --> 00:55:58.110
and you're still working
it through somehow.

00:55:58.110 --> 00:55:59.410
And when you actually sit down,

00:55:59.410 --> 00:56:01.110
you've already done
a lot of thinking.

00:56:01.110 --> 00:56:02.910
So it's okay.

00:56:02.910 --> 00:56:04.240
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly: Okay.

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:07.060
But the other thing that
I thought was I really,

00:56:07.060 --> 00:56:11.870
I felt an obligation to really
get the stories of these women,

00:56:11.870 --> 00:56:14.120
you know, right, because I
wasn't writing about myself,

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:15.880
I was writing about them.

00:56:15.880 --> 00:56:19.980
And so I felt a tremendous
amount of pressure

00:56:19.980 --> 00:56:22.220
to represent their stories
in a way that was fair.

00:56:22.220 --> 00:56:23.590
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: How
about their families?

00:56:23.590 --> 00:56:25.130
Thank you for asking
that question,

00:56:25.130 --> 00:56:27.770
because it prompts
this question.

00:56:27.770 --> 00:56:29.070
How about their families?

00:56:29.070 --> 00:56:32.360
How did they feel
when they saw the book

00:56:32.360 --> 00:56:35.200
and when they saw the
movie and when, you know,

00:56:35.200 --> 00:56:37.860
the families of these women?

00:56:37.860 --> 00:56:40.210
Because it wasn't
just the women.

00:56:40.210 --> 00:56:42.970
It was the families as well.

00:56:44.310 --> 00:56:47.370
&gt;&gt; Donna Gigliotti: We
went down to Hampton

00:56:47.370 --> 00:56:51.110
to show Katherine
Johnson the film,

00:56:51.110 --> 00:56:54.450
which is really a
nerve-racking experience.

00:56:54.450 --> 00:56:58.140
Because, you know, you have
her life in your hands,

00:56:58.140 --> 00:56:59.440
which you're portraying.

00:56:59.440 --> 00:57:02.550
And her two daughters
were with her.

00:57:02.550 --> 00:57:06.540
And she gets around
principally in a wheelchair,

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:08.640
so we had rented out a
movie theater in Hampton,

00:57:08.640 --> 00:57:13.790
and her daughters, and she
came and watched the film.

00:57:13.790 --> 00:57:16.000
And, I mean, I was
in the back thinking,

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:17.300
I don't know, I don't know.

00:57:17.300 --> 00:57:22.790
And then I heard snuffling and
there were a lot of hankies

00:57:22.790 --> 00:57:26.620
that were being spread
among these three women.

00:57:26.620 --> 00:57:28.230
And that's when I
knew we were okay.

00:57:28.230 --> 00:57:29.530
And she came out, and both

00:57:29.530 --> 00:57:33.150
of her daughters were
very moved by it.

00:57:33.150 --> 00:57:36.850
And Katherine, again,
I think she's,

00:57:36.850 --> 00:57:39.790
she's not an overly
effusive personality,

00:57:39.790 --> 00:57:42.120
but she approved of it.

00:57:42.120 --> 00:57:45.440
And that was a big deal.

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:46.880
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Yeah,
generous, actually,

00:57:46.880 --> 00:57:49.130
when someone is recording
your life like that.

00:57:49.130 --> 00:57:50.430
&gt;&gt; Donna Gigliotti: Exactly.

00:57:50.430 --> 00:57:52.100
&gt;&gt; Marie Arana: Well, I want
to congratulate you, Margot,

00:57:52.100 --> 00:57:53.640
and I want to congratulate
you, Donna.

00:57:53.640 --> 00:57:58.250
You have done wonderful work
in bringing these stories to us

00:57:58.250 --> 00:58:00.660
as an audience, as a public.

00:58:00.660 --> 00:58:03.080
And we just want more
of these stories.

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:05.510
So keep it up.

00:58:05.510 --> 00:58:20.270
[ Applause ]

00:58:20.270 --> 00:58:24.720
You can find Margot out
there signing books,

00:58:24.720 --> 00:58:28.480
and I hope you will
take the opportunity

00:58:28.480 --> 00:58:30.400
to meet her and say hello.

00:58:30.400 --> 00:58:36.500
Thank you for coming.

00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:38.490
Thank you very much.

00:58:38.490 --> 00:58:39.790
&gt;&gt; Margot Shetterly:
That was great.

00:58:39.790 --> 00:58:41.090
&gt;&gt; Donna Gigliotti:
That was fun.

